{
  "doc_id": "11417",
  "text": "eIF4B also interacts with the eIF4F complex [CITATION_1] . It contains two RNA-binding domains, interacts with eIF4A, and stimulates its RNA helicase activity [CITATION_2] . eIF4B is a substrate for phosphorylation by S6 kinase [CITATION_3] . It is suggested that the phosphorylation of eIF4B by S6 kinases (which are regulated by mTOR; see Control of Translation Elongation) stimulates its function. Indeed, this phosphorylation event favors recruitment of eIF4B into complexes with eIF3, which promotes the recruitment of ribosomes to the 5' end of the message [CITATION_4] . This likely serves to bring eIF4B to complexes containing eIF4G/4A and enhance RNA unwinding during active translation initiation.",
